            "title": "The Leicester and Swannington Railway",
            "summary": "One of the earliest steam railways in the world An image representing July 17th 1832. A celebration for the opening&hellip;",
            "content_html": "<table cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\"><figure class=\"post__image\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//01.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"542\" height=\"324\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/01-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/01-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/01-md.png 768w\"></figure>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"> </span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>One of the earliest steam railways in the world</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">An image representing July 17</span><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: xx-small;\"><sup>th</sup></span><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"> 1832.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>A celebration for the opening of the railway from Leicester to Bagworth. The railway provided passenger and freight services.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Its main purpose; to transport coal from the burgeoning<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Leicestershire coalfield.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>The Bagwoth Incline…</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">Walk down Park Lane, by the Bagworth allotments, cross the railway bridge and turn right down the obvious footpath.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>You are standing at the top of the Bagworth incline; the original course of the railway.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>The railway was rerouted to its current path in xxxx.</span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\"><figure class=\"post__image\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//02.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"618\" height=\"341\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/02-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/02-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/02-md.png 768w\"></figure>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"> </span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>…and the Roundhouse</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">Continue your walk for a short distance and obvious pile of rubble on the left is all that remains of the Bagworth Winding House known as the Round House.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>Here heavy ropes looped around a pulley to allow gravity, and the heavily laden trucks, to pull the empty trucks back up the incline.</span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\"><figure class=\"post__image\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//03.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"517\" height=\"321\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/03-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/03-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/03-md.png 768w\"></figure>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"> </span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\"><figure class=\"post__image\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//04.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"510\" height=\"287\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/04-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/04-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/04-md.png 768w\"></figure>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"> </span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>A Rerouting</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">The use of the incline was never fully satisfactory and in 1848 the line was rerouted with gradient minimised by embankments and road bridges to its present path.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<figure class=\"post__image\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//05.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"907\" height=\"512\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/05-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/05-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/05-md.png 768w\"></figure>  </span></span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>A close Encounter</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">The colliery sidings left the main railway close to Bagworth and Ellistown Station at the end of Railway Terrace,<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">  </span>crossing Station Road near to the allotment gates.</span></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\"><strong>Locomotives</strong></span></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;\">The first locomotives, Comet and Phoenix, were primitive steam engines which lacked the power to climb the incline without assistance</span></p>\n</td>\n<td valign=\"middle\">\n<figure class=\"post__image\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//06.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"485\" height=\"316\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px\" srcset=\"https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/06-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/06-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/6//responsive/06-md.png 768w\"></figure>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>",
